<td>
<p>The foundations of the rigorous study of <span class="textit">analysis</span> were laid in the nineteenth century, notably by the mathematicians Cauchy and Weierstrass. Central to the study of this subject are the formal definitions of <span class="textit">limits</span> and <span class="textit">continuity</span>.</p>
<p>Let <span class="MATH"><img align="bottom" alt="$ D$" border="0" height="17" src="http://encyclopedia-dev.springerwiki.com/cache/objects/135/l2h/img1.png" title="$ D$" width="21" /></span> be a subset of <span class="MATH"><img align="bottom" alt="$ \bf R$" border="0" height="17" src="http://encyclopedia-dev.springerwiki.com/cache/objects/135/l2h/img2.png" title="$ \bf R$" width="21" /></span> and let <span class="MATH"><img align="middle" alt="$ f \colon D \to \mathbf{R}$" border="0" height="34" src="http://encyclopedia-dev.springerwiki.com/cache/objects/135/l2h/img3.png" title="$ f \colon D \to \mathbf{R}$" width="91" /></span> be a real-valued function on <span class="MATH"><img align="bottom" alt="$ D$" border="0" height="17" src="http://encyclopedia-dev.springerwiki.com/cache/objects/135/l2h/img4.png" title="$ D$" width="21" /></span> . The function <span class="MATH"><img align="middle" alt="$ f$" border="0" height="34" src="http://encyclopedia-dev.springerwiki.com/cache/objects/135/l2h/img5.png" title="$ f$" width="16" /></span> is said to be <span class="textit">continuous</span> on <span class="MATH"><img align="bottom" alt="$ D$" border="0" height="17" src="http://encyclopedia-dev.springerwiki.com/cache/objects/135/l2h/img6.png" title="$ D$" width="21" /></span> if, for all <span class="MATH"><img align="middle" alt="$ \epsilon &gt; 0$" border="0" height="33" src="http://encyclopedia-dev.springerwiki.com/cache/objects/135/l2h/img7.png" title="$ \epsilon &gt; 0$" width="47" /></span> and for all <span class="MATH"><img align="middle" alt="$ x \in D$" border="0" height="34" src="http://encyclopedia-dev.springerwiki.com/cache/objects/135/l2h/img8.png" title="$ x \in D$" width="55" /></span> , there exists some <span class="MATH"><img align="middle" alt="$ \delta &gt; 0$" border="0" height="34" src="http://encyclopedia-dev.springerwiki.com/cache/objects/135/l2h/img9.png" title="$ \delta &gt; 0$" width="48" /></span> (which may depend on <span class="MATH"><img align="bottom" alt="$ x$" border="0" height="17" src="http://encyclopedia-dev.springerwiki.com/cache/objects/135/l2h/img10.png" title="$ x$" width="15" /></span> ) such that if <span class="MATH"><img align="middle" alt="$ y \in D$" border="0" height="34" src="http://encyclopedia-dev.springerwiki.com/cache/objects/135/l2h/img11.png" title="$ y \in D$" width="54" /></span> satisfies</p>
<div align="center" class="mathdisplay"><img align="middle" alt="$\displaystyle \vert y - x\vert &lt; \delta $" border="0" height="37" src="http://encyclopedia-dev.springerwiki.com/cache/objects/135/l2h/img12.png" title="$\displaystyle \vert y - x\vert &lt; \delta $" width="93" /></div>
then
<div align="center" class="mathdisplay"><img align="middle" alt="$\displaystyle \vert f(y) - f(x)\vert &lt; \epsilon. $" border="0" height="37" src="http://encyclopedia-dev.springerwiki.com/cache/objects/135/l2h/img13.png" title="$\displaystyle \vert f(y) - f(x)\vert &lt; \epsilon. $" width="149" /></div>
<p>One may readily verify that if <span class="MATH"><img align="middle" alt="$ f$" border="0" height="34" src="http://encyclopedia-dev.springerwiki.com/cache/objects/135/l2h/img14.png" title="$ f$" width="16" /></span> and <span class="MATH"><img align="middle" alt="$ g$" border="0" height="33" src="http://encyclopedia-dev.springerwiki.com/cache/objects/135/l2h/img15.png" title="$ g$" width="14" /></span> are continuous functions on <span class="MATH"><img align="bottom" alt="$ D$" border="0" height="17" src="http://encyclopedia-dev.springerwiki.com/cache/objects/135/l2h/img16.png" title="$ D$" width="21" /></span> then the functions <span class="MATH"><img align="middle" alt="$ f+g$" border="0" height="34" src="http://encyclopedia-dev.springerwiki.com/cache/objects/135/l2h/img17.png" title="$ f+g$" width="49" /></span> , <span class="MATH"><img align="middle" alt="$ f-g$" border="0" height="34" src="http://encyclopedia-dev.springerwiki.com/cache/objects/135/l2h/img18.png" title="$ f-g$" width="49" /></span> and <span class="MATH"><img align="middle" alt="$ f.g$" border="0" height="34" src="http://encyclopedia-dev.springerwiki.com/cache/objects/135/l2h/img19.png" title="$ f.g$" width="30" /></span> are continuous. If in addition <span class="MATH"><img align="middle" alt="$ g$" border="0" height="33" src="http://encyclopedia-dev.springerwiki.com/cache/objects/135/l2h/img20.png" title="$ g$" width="14" /></span> is everywhere non-zero then <span class="MATH"><img align="middle" alt="$ f/g$" border="0" height="37" src="http://encyclopedia-dev.springerwiki.com/cache/objects/135/l2h/img21.png" width="35" /></span> is continuous.</p>
